post_text: Today Madill Public Schools was notified of a positive COVID-19 case in Madill High School. We are working in collaboration with the Marshall County Health Department to determine those impacted through contact tracing; those affected have already been or are being notified this evening. We will continue to monitor the situation to ensure the safety of our staff and students. While we are committed to communicating transparently with our families, staff, and community, we must also protect the privacy of the students involved. We are following CDC guidelines, as well as protocols and procedure set by the local and state health departments to decrease the potential spread.

Back to School and Beyond Plan

During the past few months, we have been working on our back to school plan for safety and learning. Our students and their families are very important to us. https://www.madillok.com/

post_text: In order to address the drastic change to education during the COVID-19 pandemic, Madill Public School will move the first day of student instruction to August 20, 2020. This decision is based on so many different factors. Primarily, the more time we give our staff to become more comfortable with new COVID- safety procedures and the new learning management system, the more successful the school year will be. This additional time will be used for professional learning and strategies that will support students transitioning back to the classroom. Delaying the start of school will also allow us to monitor the number of positive cases and the levels of community spread.

We would encourage all athletes to practice social distancing and wear a protective face covering during this event.

Oklahoma‚Äôs Promise: ALERT for 10th-Grade Parents with Recent Income Loss
https://www.okhighered.org/okpromise/

If your student is or was in the 10th grade during the 2019-20 school year and you anticipate that your 2020 income may be under the $55,000 application limit for the Oklahoma‚Äôs Promise scholarship due to recent reductions in your income, you may submit an application based on your 2020 estimated income. The application must be submitted prior to the June 30, 2020 deadline at
https://secure.okcollegestart.org/applications/Oklahoma_Promise/apply.html?application_id=3544.

You will be required to provide a copy of your 2020 federal tax return when completed to verify that your 2020 income was under $55,000. The application will be held as pending until the tax documentation is received.

Please send any questions to okpromise@osrhe.edu.

8th graders participated in Acts of Kindness Week. They mowed neighbors lawns, baked cookies, brownies and cakes. They left thank you notes in mailboxes for mail carriers, and received notes thanking them for their kindness. They made special bookmarks for friends and family. They took time to play games and made artwork and crafts. They washed dishes and helped clean. They delivered flowers and wrote letters to those they missed. ‚ù§Ô∏è
No act of kindness was too small. We are so proud to call them Wildcats and to add in the love, we created a feel good video to share.
Kindness Starts with You!

Trent Wesley Harvey

Son of Christopher Harvey, his #1 biggest fan and his rock.

I lived in Madill from the age of 8 until my freshman year. I moved away for two years, then came back to my roots in Madill and started playing Basketball for the Wildcats & Coach Weiberg. I have loved playing video games ever since I was 5. Call of Duty is my favorite game. I want to thank my Aunt Savannah and Uncle Chase for helping me throughout my school years. Just letting y‚Äôall know I couldn't do it without you guys and I will forever be grateful. For my Dad, thank you for teaching me and showing me the right way to be a young, respectable man. I can't thank you enough. I will continue being great for you and I will never give up. I love you pops.

My future plans are to be a Video Production and Video Editor.

post_text:
Attention Middle School Students and Parents:

This is a note of clarification regarding the enrichment that went out today via our website and by teachers. It is our intention that as many students as possible do their assignments via Google classroom. Each teacher has a classroom set up virtually for those students that have access to an electronic device, even a cell phone with data access will view these lessons. The packet that was posted to the website earlier today was intended for those students who did not have access to Google classroom. Going forward if you need a home based packet, please contact the middle school office or pick up the packet in front of the Madill Elementary School on Monday or Wednesday from 10am-12pm. Please have patience with us, we truly want what is best for each child in our district. With that being said, this is new to all of us, if we can be of any assistance, please don't hesitate to call us.

Each teacher has a classroom set up virtually for those students that have access to an electronic device, even a cell phone with data access will view these lessons. The packet that was posted to the website earlier today was intended for those students who did not have access to Google classroom. Going forward if you need a home based packet, please contact the middle school office or pick up the packet in front of the Madill Elementary School on Monday or Wednesday from 10am-12pm. Please have patience with us, we truly want what is best for each child in our district. With that being said, this is new to all of us, if we can be of any assistance, please don't hesitate to call us.

Hofmeister proposes State Board of Education approve continuous learning for students starting April 6, school buildings to remain closed

Oklahoma State Department of Education
March 23 at 3:30 PM ¬∑

LATEST UPDATE: State Superintendent Joy Hofmeister announced today that she will propose a Continuous Learning Plan (distance learning) to the State Board of Education this week to complete the school year for Oklahoma students without reopening school buildings during the global pandemic.

The Board will hold a special meeting on Wednesday, March 25. Board members will meet virtually.

‚ÄúWe are determined to support our Pre-K through high school students as well as English learners, special education students and those who need reinforced skills or additional enrichment. We recognize this reality will present challenges for many families and districts, but these are extraordinary times that call for extraordinary measures. This coordinated, swift and thoughtful action will help safeguard the health and well-being of our communities, students and professionals in public schools. We must do absolutely everything in our power to reduce transmission of coronavirus.‚Äù - State Supt. Joy Hofmeister

Larry Case
Superintendent

post_text:
PreK classes learned about germs and how to wash their hands today! üñê

As the students were greeted by employees of the health department, they shook their hands. (Unaware they were spreading germs!) Then they watched a short video to explain hand washing. Afterward, the students practiced pretend washing while they sat and waited. If you have a PreK student, ask them about each step, what to use, and how long they need to wash!

Then, each student took their turn placing hands under the ultraviolet light to see their germs. Next, they washed their hands and came back to see their success. The oohs and aahs made there way across the classroom. Much giggling was heard.

The classes were asked when they should wash their hands: after playing outside, after touching their pets, and before eating were all times they discussed. These are some smart kids!

üñê Hands down, this was a great way to learn about hand washing and those yucky germs! ü¶†

It fills the halls with visual kindness and serves as a reminder to be kind.

‚ÄúWe want to encourage the students to be kind and say something nice to someone random, not just their usual friends.‚Äù Said counselor Debbie Allen.

‚ÄúShe‚Äôs all about the hearts!‚Äù Secretary Jessica Neeley happily stated about Mrs. Allen.

It‚Äôs a lovely sight looking down the hall and seeing the lockers fill up with hearts as Valentine‚Äôs Day approaches. The students enjoy discovering a heart of kindness appear on their lockers. They look forward to this small act of kindness which encourages them to do an act of kindness for another classmate.

You really can‚Äôt ever have enough kindness! ‚ù§Ô∏è

post_text:
Today kicks off a community wide shared reading event called One School, One Book!

This event is for students at MES and the ECC. The book chosen for the ECC is Charlotte's Web. MES students and families will be reading Friendship According to Humphrey. Both books were selected because of their ability to be followed, understood, and enjoyed by younger students while still captivating and stimulating older children.

Each student will receive a copy of the book for them to keep along with a reading schedule. Parents are encouraged to read the book aloud to their child even if they are able to read the book themselves. Students will have the opportunity to answer trivia questions about the book each morning for a chance to win a prize. The goal is to have the entire school community reading and talking about the same book. This program is made possible by the Oklahoma Striving Readers Comprehensive Literacy grant.

post_text:
Lauren Campbell, reporter for MMS Student Council, wrote the following article:

Madill Middle School Student Council held a fundraiser called Coins for Kids from October 1- 15, 2019. The fundraiser was to help raise money for St. Jude Children‚Äôs Research Hospital. There was also a competition between grades 6-8. Each grade had a bucket and whichever grade had the most money in their bucket on the 15th, got to keep their money for field trips, parties, and other activities of their choice. Eighth grade won with a total of $158.88. Sixth grade placed second with a total of $122.22, and seventh grade came in third place raising a total of $105.18.

The eighth graders then voted unanimously to donate the money they raised as well. All together, $386.28 was sent to St. Jude. Thank you to all the people who participated; your help is greatly appreciated!

There was also a competition between grades 6-8. Each grade had a bucket and whichever grade had the most money in their bucket on the 15th, got to keep their money for field trips, parties, and other activities of their choice. Eighth grade won with a total of $158.88. Sixth grade placed second with a total of $122.22, and seventh grade came in third place raising a total of $105.18.

The eighth graders then voted unanimously to donate the money they raised as well. All together, $386.28 was sent to St. Jude. Thank you to all the people who participated; your help is greatly appreciated!

post_text:
Mrs. Jefferson‚Äôs 1st grade class made Turkey Glyphs. Parts of the turkey represent the student. ü¶É

For instance, if a student is a girl, they have an orange beak. If the student is a boy, their beak is yellow. Each turkey has feathers which represents the age of the student. If the turkey has red feet, it means they are an only child. Yellow feet means the student has a sibling. The eyes of the turkey match that of the student. Most importantly, does the student like to eat turkey? If so, they color the body brown. If not, the turkey is black. All of her little turkeys did a great job!

post_text:
ü¶É As Thanksgiving Break quickly approaches, the halls of the ECC are covered in thankfulness, creative turkey feathers and recipes! Kindergarten students were asked to describe how to cook a turkey. Their answers made us giggle & grin.

Some students went to the woods to get their turkey, while others drove to Walmart. One even bought their turkey at McDonalds! This must be a seasonal item only available in November.

Not everyone took time to thaw or season their turkey. Most used salt, pepper or even pepperonis! My favorite is what I refer to as the dessert turkey... it had marshmallows, candy and gummy bears! Yum.

The majority of the students had a short amount of cooking time for their turkey. One as short as 10 seconds!

If you‚Äôre still looking for a turkey recipe, be sure to check out this week‚Äôs Madill Record to learn all the different ways to Cook a Turkey! ü¶É

MMS Cheerleaders competed last Saturday in Choctaw for the Junior High State Championship. They performed a cheer and a routine with the school fight song. The team is made up of seventeen members currently in the 7th and 8th grade. They tried out last April to make the team for the 2019-20 school year. The team started practices in the summer.

When the school year began, they went to once a week practices. They have been committed to working together and learning from one another. The team has grown in experience and it shows. The students have a full course load and also participate in many other school electives. Coach Melissa Gray said, ‚ÄúMany of the cheerleaders are also active in band, vocal music, student council, art, 4H, basketball, cross country, softball and track.‚Äù

This is the first year the team competed in the event. Coach Amanda Rushing said, ‚ÄúThey did a great job and did everything asked of them.‚Äù They performed stunts and a successful routine. Although the team came up short, they did an amazing job and learned a lot. Way to go Wildcats! üêæ

F is for FIREFIGHTER

Pre-K students study a letter each week. At the beginning of school, they started with the letter A. This week is the letter F.

The Madill Fire Department helped learn about the letter F. They went to the ECC and explained the job of a firefighter and fire safety.

Mrs. Mancini asked Mrs. Brown‚Äôs class, ‚ÄúWhat number do you call if you have a fire?‚Äù The students yelled out, ‚Äú911!‚Äù

Henleigh replied, ‚ÄúIf the fire is in your house, you put a towel under your door.‚Äù

Eriana told her, ‚ÄúYou have to get on the ground and roll!‚Äù

Our little cats sure learned a lot about fire safety. It was fun asking them about the letter of the week. Fun, that‚Äôs the letter F!
